articles.description: Iowa Governor Kim Reynolds is expected to endorse Florida Governor Ron DeSantis for the 2024 presidential race, providing a potential boost to DeSantis, who trails behind former President Donald Trump in the Republican nomination race. Reynolds will appear at a DeSantis rally in Iowa on Monday. DeSantis has focused heavily on Iowa, believing a strong showing in the state could help him close the gap with Trump. The Trump campaign responded to the endorsement news by criticizing Reynolds for previously declaring neutrality in the race.
articles.title: Iowa governor Reynolds to endorse DeSantis' presidential candidacy: Sources

articles.description: More than 20 people were killed in Sudan after shells hit a market in a suburb of the capital, Khartoum. The fighting between army chief Abdel Fattah al-Burhan and his former deputy Mohamed Hamdan Daglo has been ongoing since April. The conflict has resulted in over 10,000 deaths and 5.5 million people being displaced, according to estimates by the United Nations. The actual toll is believed to be higher as many of the wounded and killed do not reach hospitals or morgues.
articles.title: More than 20 killed in Sudan after shell hits Khartoum market: NGO

articles.description: Ohio voters will decide on Tuesday whether to add explicit protections for abortion rights to the state's constitution. The referendum will determine whether the constitution guarantees the freedom to make reproductive decisions, including abortion. The US Supreme Court revoked the national right to abortion last year, leaving it up to individual states to decide. Ohio currently has a law that would ban abortions after a heartbeat is detected, but it is temporarily suspended due to legal challenges.
articles.title: Ohio vote tests abortion question one year ahead of 2024 race

articles.description: The office of President Volodymyr Zelensky on Saturday chastised Ukraine's top military commander for publicly declaring the war at a stalemate, suggesting the comments would help the Russian invasion. It was a striking public rebuke that signaled an emerging rift between the military and civilian leadership at a challenging time for Ukraine. The public censure of Zaluzhny came a day after the president's office replaced one of his deputies, the head of special operations forces, who after his firing said he had been blindsided by the dismissal.
articles.title: In rift with military, Zelensky slams top gen for 'war at stalemate' remark

articles.description: PM Netanyahu disciplined on Sunday a junior member of his cabinet who appeared to voice openness to the idea of Israel carrying out a nuclear strike on Gaza. Netanyahu's office said in a statement that the minister concerned - heritage minister Amihay Eliyahu from a far-right party in the coalition government - had been suspended from cabinet meetings "until further notice".  "Eliyahu's statements are not based in reality. Israel and the IDF (military) are operating in accordance with the highest standards of international law," Netanyahu's office said.
articles.title: Netanyahu's minister says nuking Gaza an option, draws Bibi's ire

articles.description: Protesters gathered outside the residence of Israeli PM Benjamin Netanyahu to express their anger at the failures that led to last month's deadly attack by Hamas gunmen. The protest coincided with a poll showing that over three-quarters of Israelis believe Netanyahu should resign. Netanyahu has not taken personal responsibility for the failures that allowed the surprise assault, which has led to growing public fury and criticism of the government's response. A majority of Israelis blame Netanyahu for the attack, according to the poll.
articles.title: Anger against Netanyahu rises as Israelis amass outside his home

articles.description: A hostage situation at Hamburg airport in Germany came to an end after 18 hours. The man, who had driven his vehicle through the gates with his 4-year-old daughter inside, was arrested and the girl is unharmed. The airport had been closed since Saturday night when the armed man broke through a gate and fired shots. The man's wife had previously reported a child abduction, and it is believed to be a custody battle. No one was injured during the standoff.
articles.title: Hostage crisis at German airport ends after 18 hrs

articles.description: President Biden is trailing behind Donald Trump in five out of six battleground states, according to polls by the New York Times and Siena College. Voters have doubts about Biden's age and are dissatisfied with his handling of the economy and other issues. Biden is only ahead in Wisconsin, while Trump leads in Arizona, Georgia, Michigan, Nevada, and Pennsylvania. The polls also show that voters across income levels feel Biden's policies have hurt them personally, while they credit Trump's policies for helping them.
articles.title: Trump leads in 5 of 6 key battleground US states as voters blast Biden: Polls

articles.description: Elon Musk on Saturday unveiled details of his new AI tool called "Grok", which can access X in real time and will be initially available to the social.
articles.title: Musk teases AI chatbot 'Grok' with real-time access to X

articles.description: US Secretary of State Antony Blinken has stated that the Palestinian Authority should have a central role in the future of Gaza. Blinken made the comments during his visit to the region amid escalating tensions over Israel's war with Hamas. He met with Palestinian Authority President Mahmoud Abbas in Ramallah and then traveled to Iraq. Blinken also discussed the need for humanitarian pauses in the fighting and addressed the threats from Iranian-aligned militias. He is seeking discussions on how Gaza could be governed after the destruction of Hamas.
articles.title: Blinken says Palestinian voices key to Gaza future

articles.description: More than 300 Americans and their families have been evacuated from Gaza, but negotiations are ongoing for the release of hostages taken by Hamas. The exact number of remaining US citizens in Gaza is unknown. Efforts are being made to resume evacuations of injured Gazans and foreign passport holders through the Rafah crossing. President Joe Biden has called for a pause in hostilities to allow hostages to be released, and the White House supports a humanitarian pause for aid deliveries to Gaza. Over 9,770 Palestinians have been killed in the conflict.
articles.title: More than 300 Americans got out of Gaza, more remain, White House says

articles.description: Four civilians, including three children, were killed in an Israeli airstrike in southern Lebanon. The strike was carried out by the Israeli military in response to a strike launched by the Lebanese militant group Hezbollah, which resulted in the death of one Israeli. The clashes between Israeli troops and Hezbollah militants along the Lebanon-Israel border have been escalating since the start of the Hamas-Israel war. The death toll of civilians on the Lebanese side has now reached 14, with Hezbollah warning of retaliation if Lebanese civilians are targeted.
articles.title: A woman and 3 children are killed by an Israeli airstrike in south Lebanon, local officials say

articles.description: The Israel Defence Forces (IDF) have shared video evidence of Hamas rocket launchers being placed near a children's swimming pool and a playground in the northern Gaza Strip. The IDF has accused Hamas of committing war crimes by deliberately placing rocket launchers near civilian sites. The videos and pictures provided by the IDF show rocket launchers positioned within a residential neighborhood and a children's playground. The IDF has condemned Hamas for using the civilian population as a human shield for terror purposes.
articles.title: Israel uncovers Hamas rocket launchers next to children's pool, playground

articles.description: Four Palestinians were killed during Israeli military raids in the occupied West Bank, according to the Palestinian health ministry and Israeli army. The violence occurred amidst the Israel-Hamas war. Two men were killed in an attack by Israeli forces in Abu Dis, while a third Palestinian, allegedly affiliated with the Islamic State group, was shot dead in a fire exchange. Another Palestinian was killed in Nuba during clashes with Israeli soldiers. Since the start of the war, over 150 Palestinians have been killed in the West Bank, and over 1,000 have been arrested.
articles.title: Israel forces kill four Palestinians in West Bank

articles.description: Israel cut internet and phone lines in the Gaza Strip Sunday night, for the third time since the start of the Israel-Hamas war on October 7, telecoms firm Paltel said. "We regret to announce the complete shutdown of communications and internet services in Gaza after the Israeli side disconnected the servers," Paltel said in a statement. However, soon Israeli army launched intense bombardment on Gaza city and other nearby zones which could be heard in Rafah.
articles.title: Internet, phone lines cut again in Gaza: Telecoms firm

articles.description: Israeli President Isaac Herzog accepted the credentials of newly appointed US Ambassador to Israel Jack Lew. The appointment was fast-tracked due to the escalating conflict between Hamas and Israel in Gaza. During the credential-receiving ceremony, President Herzog expressed gratitude for the support of the United States and emphasized the importance of the friendship between the two countries. Ambassador Lew acknowledged the challenging times and pledged to prioritize working towards securing the release of hostages held by Hamas.
articles.title: US envoy to Israel submits credentials to Pres Herzog, takes charge

articles.description: External Affairs Minister S Jaishankar spoke with his Iranian counterpart, Hossein Amir-Abdollahian, to discuss the serious situation arising from the Israel-Hamas conflict. "Spoke today with Iranian Foreign Minister Amir Abdollahian. Discussed the grave situation in West Asia and the concern of the international community," the external affairs minister posted on 'X'. "Conveyed the importance of preventing escalation and providing humanitarian support. Agreed to stay in touch," he said.
articles.title: Israel-Hamas conflict: EAM Jaishankar speaks to Iranian counterpart, discusses 'grave' situation

articles.description: Three Iranians who were allegedly agents of Israel's Mossad spy agency have been detained in a joint operation with the Taliban in Afghanistan, according to state television in Iran. It said that the detainees were said to be planning kamikaze drone attacks from the Afghan border into Iran. News of the arrests came after a Taliban delegation arrived in Tehran on Saturday for meetings with top officials including Foreign Minister Hossein Amir-Abdollahian.
articles.title: 'Israeli spies' held in joint operation with Afghanistan: Iran

articles.description: Japan came in last in a global ranking of employees' well being, measured by assessing physical, mental, social and spiritual health, the results of a survey conducted by McKinsey health institute showed. The island nation scored 25% in the poll of more than 30,000 workers across 30 countries, according to the study. Turkiye was highest at 78%, followed by 76% for India and 75% for China. The global average was 57%. According to the survey, employees who had positive work experiences reported better holistic health, are more innovative at work and show higher job performance.
articles.title: In global employee well-being survey, India second after Turkiye; Japan last

articles.description: Sam Bankman-Fried, the founder of FTX cryptocurrency exchange, has been convicted of fraud by a New York jury. The jury found him guilty of stealing at least $10 billion from customers and investors. Bankman-Fried, once worth over $20 billion, is now facing a maximum sentence of 110 years. The conviction is a significant victory for US attorney Damian Williams, who described Bankman-Fried's actions as "one of the biggest financial frauds in US history." Bankman-Fried is expected to appeal the verdict.
articles.title: FTX crypto mogul convicted of fraud, faces max of 110 yrs in jail

articles.description: The US has been flying surveillance drones over Gaza in search of hostages taken by Hamas when the Palestinian militant group attacked Israel on Oct. 7, two US officials said. The officials said the US was flying intelligence gathering drones over Gaza to assist with hostage location efforts. One of the officials said they had been carrying out the drone flights for over a week. US officials said 10 Americans who remain unaccounted for may be among the more than 200 taken as hostages into Gaza, where they are believed to be held in Hamas' extensive tunnel network.
articles.title: US drones fly over Gaza in search for American hostages

articles.description: Hezbollah leader Hassan Nasrallah said Friday that his powerful militia is already engaged in unprecedented cross-border fighting with Israel along the Lebanon-Israel border and threatened a further escalation. In the televised remarks - Nasrallah's first since the beginning of the Hamas-Israel war - he stopped short of announcing that his Lebanese militia would fully enter the war, a move that would have devastating consequences for both Lebanon and Israel.
articles.title: Hezbollah chief threatens escalation

articles.author: Omer Farooq Khan
articles.description: Afghanistan slammed Pakistan for the treatment meted out to its nationals, saying the decision to expel refugees was "unilateral" as it was taken by Islamabad without consulting Kabul. In an audio clip shared on social media, Afghanistan's interim defence minister, Mullah Muhammad Yaqub Mujahid, criticised Pakistan's caretaker government, headed by a military-sponsored PM of Pashtun-origin, Anwaarul Haq Kakar, for failing to consider the consequences of its action expelling refugees.
articles.title: Afghanistan slams Pakistan, says expelling refugees move 'unilateral'

articles.description: The Kremlin on Friday dismissed a Wall Street Journal report that United States intelligence believed Russia's Wagner mercenary group plans to provide Hezbollah with an air defence system, saying such talk was unfounded. "We have already said that, de-facto, such a group (Wagner) does not exist," Kremlin spokesman Dmitry Peskov said. "All of these musings are as a rule based on nothing and have no foundation," Peskov said when asked about the report.
articles.title: Wagner to give Hezbollah air defence system? Kremlin dismisses report

articles.description: US Secretary of State Antony Blinken has called on Israel to temporarily halt its military offensive in Gaza to allow for aid to enter the Palestinian enclave. However, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has rejected the idea unless the Hamas militants release the 240 hostages they are holding. Blinken has emphasized the need for Israel to protect Palestinian civilians in Gaza. The US has dismissed international calls for a ceasefire but has sought to persuade Israel to accept localized pauses.
articles.title: Bibi rules out Gaza ceasefire as Blinken seeks civilian protection

articles.description: Meta Platforms Inc. Chief Executive Officer Mark Zuckerberg underwent surgery to repair a torn knee ligament sustained during a mixed martial arts session, he said Friday in a post on Instagram. “Tore my ACL sparring and just got out of surgery to replace it,” Zuckerberg wrote in the caption of a post with a series of photos showing him in a hospital bed, his knee bandaged and in a brace. The CEO, 39, said he plans to continuing his training for “a competitive MMA fight early next year.”
articles.title: Mark Zuckerberg undergoes surgery for martial arts knee injury

articles.description: The Army reservist who carried out the shootings in a bowling alley and a bar in Lewiston, Maine, was alive and potentially on the run for more than 24 hours after the incident, according to the state's medical examiner. Robert Card died from a self-inflicted gunshot, which likely occurred eight to 12 hours before his body was found in a tractor-trailer. Concerns about Card's mental state had been raised prior to the shootings, and law enforcement agencies came under scrutiny for not finding his body sooner.
articles.title: Maine mass shooter was alive for most of massive 2-day search, autopsy suggests

articles.description: A Chinese art gallery, The Paintings Say Arirang, is openly selling North Korean art in Beijing, despite UN sanctions prohibiting such sales. The gallery, which operates a studio for North Korean artists, showcases the unique socialist realist style of North Korean art that appeals to a niche audience. China's lax enforcement of the sanctions targeting North Korea's nuclear program allows for the continued sale of North Korean art. The art is seen as a form of propaganda, with artists working directly for North Korea's authorities to create art glorifying the state and its ideology.
articles.title: North Korean art sells in China despite UN sanctions over nuclear programme

articles.description: Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has rejected US calls for a humanitarian pause in the Israel-Hamas war, stating that they will continue unless the hostages held by Hamas are released. Hezbollah leader Hassan Nasrallah has also stated that his group is undeterred by US warnings to stay out of the war. Israeli troops have closed in on Gaza City, launching targeted attacks on militant cells. The death toll in the conflict continues to rise, with over 9,000 Palestinians and 1,400 Israelis killed.
articles.title: Israel rebuffs US push for humanitarian pause, says hostages must be released first

articles.description: A recent solar storm caused a unique combination of red and green lights in the night sky above Canada, creating a strange image of orange pillars. Experts say that orange auroras shouldn't exist as the color is usually overwhelmed by other colors given off by excited molecules. The phenomenon was captured in a photograph by aurora photographer Harlan Thomas, who described the orange hue as "sublime." The last time such vibrant orange auroras were seen was during the Halloween storm of 2003.
articles.title: Solar storm causes pumpkin-colored auroras to fill sky

articles.description: Ukrainian shelling in the Russian-occupied southern Kherson region resulted in the death of nine individuals, according to Moscow-installed occupational authorities. The attack occurred as Kyiv conducts a counteroffensive to regain territory from Russian forces in southern Ukraine. "Nine dead people were pulled out from under the rubble," Vladimir Saldo, the Russian-installed head of the Moscow-occupied Kherson region, told Russian state television.
articles.title: Ukraine shelling kills 9 in occupied south: local official

articles.description: Israeli President Isaac Herzog met with the ambassadors of Thailand, the Philippines, Tanzania, and Nepal to discuss the terror invasion carried out by Hamas in southwestern Israel. The ambassadors expressed concern for their citizens who were killed, injured, or taken hostage during the attack. President Herzog emphasized that Hamas does not differentiate between religions or countries and assured the ambassadors that the Israeli people appreciate their citizens. Among foreign countries, Thailand had the second-highest number of fatalities and a significant number of citizens taken hostage by Hamas. The Thai ambassador expressed concern for the well-being of the Thai people in Israel and asked for assistance in locating and helping the abducted individuals.
articles.title: Israeli President meets with envoys whose citizens were murdered and abducted by Hamas

articles.description: Hezbollah leader Hassan Nasrallah has stated that his militia is currently engaged in cross-border fighting with Israel along the Lebanon-Israel border and threatened further escalation. Nasrallah stopped short of announcing that his Lebanese militia would fully enter the war, but warned that Hezbollah is prepared for all options.  Nasrallah's speech has been widely anticipated as an indication of whether the Israel-Hamas conflict could escalate into a regional war.
articles.title: Lebanon's militant Hezbollah leader threatens escalation with Israel as its war with Hamas rages on

articles.description: Record-breaking rain produced floods in a vast swath of Italy's Tuscany region as Storm Ciaran pushed into the country overnight trapping residents in their homes, inundating hospitals and overturning cars. At least five people were killed, bringing the storm's death toll in western Europe to 12 on Friday. Italian Civil Protection authorities said 200 millimeters (nearly 8 inches) of rain fell in a three-hour period, from the coastal city of Livorno to the inland valley of Mugello, and caused riverbanks to overflow. Video shows at least a dozen cars getting pushed down a flooded road.
articles.title: Storm Ciaran kills 5, taking European death toll to 12

articles.description: US Secretary of State Antony Blinken has urged Israeli leaders to implement humanitarian pauses in their conflict with Hamas in Gaza. The purpose of these pauses would be to allow for the delivery of aid to the Palestinian enclave and facilitate the release of hostages. Blinken discussed the details of these pauses with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and the war cabinet, emphasizing the need to ensure that Hamas does not exploit the pauses for its own advantage.
articles.title: Anthony Blinken in Israel urges humanitarian pauses in Gaza war

articles.description: An Iranian court has sentenced a female gym trainer to death for adultery. The woman's husband reported her to the police after finding her with another man at their home, whom he discovered through surveillance cameras. Although Iranian law allows for appeals, the country has faced international criticism for its frequent use of the death penalty. The United Nations Secretary-General, Antonio Guterres, warned that Iran was executing people at an "alarming rate." Crimes such as adultery, sodomy, murder, rape, armed robbery, kidnapping, and drug trafficking are all punishable by death in Iran.
articles.title: Iran sentences a woman to death for adultery

articles.description: Canadian defence minister Bill Blair informed the press on Friday that a Chinese military aircraft discharged flares toward a Canadian helicopter in international waters the previous Sunday. He stated that Ottawa intends to communicate its concerns to Beijing. This marks the second instance within a two-week period where Canada has raised accusations of unsafe conduct by China's air force. In mid-October, Minister Blair reported that a Chinese fighter jet had approached within five meters (approximately 16 feet) of a surveillance aircraft engaged in a United Nations mission.
articles.title: China jet fired flares at Canadian chopper in international waters: Ottawa

articles.description: Archaeologists in Morocco have discovered a Roman-era site in Rabat, which includes a port district, bath, and cemetery dating back to the second century. The site, now the third largest in Morocco, will provide insights into the lives of Roman settlers and romanised Moroccans during that time. The bath covers an area of over 2000 square meters and resembles imperial counterparts in Rome. The excavation is ongoing to uncover the port and other parts of one of the largest Roman towns in the country.
articles.title: Morocco unearths Roman-era second century site in Rabat

articles.description: Every November 1st and 2nd, Mexico holds its largest public celebration: Día de los Muertos, or Day of the Dead, a fusion of Roman Catholic and Indigenous rituals that honor and remember deceased loved ones. Far from a mournful affair, the holiday is a time of celebration and warmth. Correspondent Enrique Acevedo talks with Mexico City's minister of culture Claudia Curiel De Icaza about the city's celebrations; with acclaimed chef Elena Reygadas about baking traditional pan de muerto; and with author Regina Marchi, who has documented the holiday's growing popularity on both sides of the border in her book, "Day of the Dead in the U.S.A."

articles.description:
Buildings destroyed after the earthquake on February 13, 2023, in Hatay, Turkey. | Murat Saka/dia images via Getty Images
    

  
Turkey is investigating and has arrested some contractors, but the entire political and economic system is implicated.
 Turkey is still in the middle of an emergency, reeling from the earthquake that killed at least 35,000 people last week. But the finger-pointing has already begun. 
The rush to punishment comes amid the grief, but also the mounting fury and frustration over the Turkish government’s earthquake response. Much of that is focused on the emergency response — waiting for aid and rescue teams — but it is also extending to anger about policies before the earthquake, about how shoddy building construction may have exacerbated the devastation of the dis…
articles.title: Who is responsible for Turkey’s bad buildings?

articles.description:
Getty Images
    

  
How we turned 20,000 Soviet nukes into zero-carbon energy — and how we can do the same with some of our own.
 Just a decade ago, one in 10 American lightbulbs was powered by dismantled Russian nuclear weapons.
That was made possible by the Megatons to Megawatts program, an agreement negotiated after the collapse of the Soviet Union to convert uranium from Russia’s nuclear weapons stockpile into fuel for US nuclear power plants. The unconventional policy was first proposed by MIT physicist Thomas Neff in a 1991 New York Times op-ed. By the time Megatons to Megawatts ran its full course from 1993 to 2013, it had eliminated about 20,000 nuclear warheads and stood out as a point of shared pride in the often jaded arms control and disarmament field. “Nearly every commercia…
articles.title: 10 years ago, we were turning nuclear bombs into nuclear energy. We can do it again.

articles.description:
Volunteers stand on rubble of a destroyed building in Kahramanmaras, Turkey, on February 7, 2023. | Adem Altan/AFP via Getty Images
    

  
What Turkey and Syria’s deadly earthquakes reveal about wealth.
 In the early hours of Monday, February 6, residents living in southern Turkey and northern Syria were woken by violent shaking, collapsing buildings, and sweeping blackouts. The earthquake buried residents in rubble and was followed by powerful aftershocks. By the following Monday, the death toll had passed 36,000 people. “It was like the apocalypse,” Abdul Salam al-Mahmoud, a resident of Atareb, Syria, told Reuters.  
The country is no stranger to quakes, having lost 17,000 people to a 7.4-magnitude tremor in 1999. But while last week’s earthquake was a 7.8-magnitude quake, and had an u…
articles.title: Why earthquakes are deadlier depending on where you live

articles.description:
A suspected Chinese spy balloon flies above Charlotte, North Carolina, on February 4, 2023.  | Peter Zay/Anadolu Agency via Getty Images
    

  
As all these objects fall, a new space race is rising.
 Now that the US military has shot down a suspected spy balloon from China and three other unidentified flying objects, there will be debates about the UFOs’ meaning, their capabilities, and why they were all up there in the first place. 
Though former CIA Director Michael Hayden said the initial balloon’s threat to the welfare of Americans was vastly inflated, others described the incident as a wake-up call. Former Trump national security adviser H.R. McMaster hopes it will lead to a “Sputnik moment,” harkening back to the US space race with the Soviet Union. The Wall Street Journal even war…
articles.title: Why the balloon and UFO affairs are a Sputnik moment

articles.author: M.L. Nestel
articles.description:
She tried to censure and it came up short. 
Now she's shaming the names who didn't vote in favor. 
Rep. Marjorie Taylor Greene (R-GA) had willed a resolution to censure Rep. Rashida Tlaib (D-MI) for her attendance of a protest opposing the war in Gaza. 
POLL: Should Trump be allowed to run for office?
"List of feckless Republicans that voted WITH Democrats to table my censure resolution against Rashida Tlaib," Greene said on Wednesday. "This is why Republicans NEVER do anything to stop the communists Democrats or ever hold anyone accountable!! PATHETIC."

She created a social media thread naming some of her friends in the House who didn't have what it took to vote with her. 
They include current House Speaker Mike Johnson, Rep. Chip Roy (R-TX), and Rep. Ken Buck (R-CO) who announced he wasn't running for reelection. 

	Earlier in the week, Greene preemptively lashed out after learning that her effort wasn't gaining a coalition in Congress.
"I want to remind you, this happened on the same day Hezbollah declared a day of immense anger," she said. "And Rashida Tlaib organized with that group. And they did. They did protest, and they did an insurrection into our Capitol complex, stopping Congress and stopping the Senate."
The media was quick to take notice of the lawmaker's swing and miss Wednesday.
"Colleague Kelly Phares rpts 23 GOPers join Dems to table or kill effort to censure Dem MI Rep Tlaib," tweeted Chat Pergram.
Melanie Zanona also tweeted: "motion to table — aka kill — MTG’s resolution to censure Rep. Rashida Tlaib just passed the House, with help of 23 Republicans."

And CNN's Manu Raju added that the effort to take on Tlaib quickly died tweeting: "House kills resolution to censure Rashida Tlaib. 23 Republicans voted with Dems. MTG offered the resolution."
articles.title: 'Pathetic': Marjorie Taylor Greene attacks 'feckless Republicans' who voted against her

articles.author: Sarah K. Burris
articles.description:
Sen. Tommy Tuberville's (R-AL) blockade appears to be coming to an end, according to an MSNBC report. 
Capitol reporter Ali Vitali said that a group of Republicans were going to take to the Senate floor and force a vote with Democrats to marginalize Tuberville's protest against military promotions that has led to a reduced military readiness for the United States, according to reports.
After a discussion about the absurdity of the protest, host Nicolle Wallace said that she recalled the era when Republicans had to be supportive of the military or they'd be shamed by leaders like Sen. Mitch McConnell (R-KY) and the GOP speaker. 
POLL: Should Trump be allowed to run for office?
Taking to social media, reporter Andrew Desiderio confirmed the reporting, saying that the floor actions will take place tonight, where they will ask for unanimous consent on ending the Tuberville blockade. He said that he was told it would be led by Sen. Dan Sullivan (R-AK). 
The news comes after reports that McConnell threatened Sen. Josh Hawley (R-MO) over his bill to stop corporations from being able to give money to campaigns. McConnell reportedly pointed to Hawley in the caucus lunch and said he wouldn't be there if it wasn't for the money from his Senate Leadership PAC. He went on to threaten any member who supported the bill with a primary. 
It's the first such action heard about from McConnell since he suffered serious injuries from a series of falls and then appeared to freeze at various public press availabilities.
articles.title: Republicans to join Dems in breaking Tuberville's blockade on military promotions: report

articles.author: M.L. Nestel
articles.description:

Eric Smith, who had been doubling as both the top No. 1 and No. 2 Marine Corps leader since July, suffered an apparent heart attack and was hospitalized on Sunday — leaving a three-star general to hold the prestigious post, according to a report published by Politico.

The potential overextension of Smith and the stalling of more than 300 critical leadership roles was iced out by Tuberville's blockade installed as a protest against the Pentagon's policy to permit time off and reimbursement for abortions.

articles.description: A new commemorative coin celebrating the King’s 75th birthday and paying tribute to his passion for the natural world has been unveiled by the Royal Mint. To mark the occasion, the Mint is looking for 75 people turning 75 years old this year, to give them a special £5 coin, in honour of the King’s birthday. To honour the King’s lifelong commitment to sustainability, a special birthday coin has also been made from a blend of silver recovered from industrial and medical x-ray films. Those celebrating their 75th birthday in 2023 can submit their name and contact details via the Royal Mint to be in with a chance of receiving an uncirculated £5 commemorative coin. The winners will be drawn at random and asked to provide photographic evidence of age. They will be contacted via email from early December 2023.

articles.description:
Massive explosions are hitting Gaza City and its surroundings as Israel continues on with its deadliest campaign to destroy Hamas following the terrorist group's unprovoked attack on October 7.

The IDF on Sunday said its troops were “encircling Gaza city” and conducting “widespread strikes”.

Health officials in the Palestinian territory claimed 53 people died in two blasts at refugee camps.

Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu reaffirmed his rejection for a ceasefire on Sunday until the some 240 hostages taken by Hamas on October 7 are released.

"There will be no ceasefire without the return of the hostages. This should be completely removed from the lexicon," Mr Netanyahu said.

"We say this to our friends and to our enemies. We will simply continue until we defeat them. We have no alternative."

Reuters: Pro-Palestinian crowds try to storm air base housing U.S. troops in Turkey 
ADANA, Turkey (Reuters) - Turkish police used tear gas and water cannon as hundreds of people at a pro-Palestinian rally on Sunday tried to storm an air base that houses U.S. troops, hours before U.S. Secretary of State Antony Blinken was due in Ankara for talks on Gaza. 
Turkey, which has stepped up its criticism of Israel as the humanitarian crisis in Gaza has worsened, supports a two-state solution while hosting members of the Palestinian militant group Hamas. Since the Israel-Hamas war started, protests have erupted across the country. 
Earlier this week, the IHH Humanitarian Relief Foundation, an Islamist Turkish aid agency, organised a convoy to travel to the Incirlik air base in the Adana province in southern Turkey to protest Israeli attacks on Gaza and U.S. support for Israel.

articles.description:
U.S. soldiers assigned to 1st Stryker Brigade Combat Team, 4th Infantry Division, fire their M777 A2 Howitzer in Syria on Sept. 30, 2021. (Cpl. Isaiah Scott/Army) 
DNYUZ/New York Times: A Secret War, Strange New Wounds, and Silence From the Pentagon 
When Javier Ortiz came home from a secret mission in Syria, the ghost of a dead girl appeared to him in his kitchen. She was pale and covered in chalky dust, as if hit by an explosion, and her eyes stared at him with a glare as dark and heavy as oil. 
The 21-year-old Marine was part of an artillery gun crew that fought against the Islamic State, and he knew that his unit’s huge cannons had killed hundreds of enemy fighters. The ghost, he was sure, was their revenge. 
A shiver went through him. He backed into another room in his apartment near Camp Pendleton in California and flicked on the lights, certain that he was imagining things. She was still there.

 
Read more .... 
 WNU Editor: This story hits close to home. My father commanded artillery units for the Soviet Army during the Second World War. Aside from suffering hearing loss, he was haunted by nightmares from that war for the rest of his life. My father's best friend (and my Godfather) also served in such a unit, and he committed suicide 20 years after the war. Everyone blamed his war experience for his suicide.
articles.title: Why Are So Many U.S. Artillery Gun Crews Who Were Deployed To Bombard The Islamic State Facing Health And Psychological Issues?

articles.description:
BNN: Russia’s Economy to Grow by 2.8% in 2023, Predicts Finance Minister 
Anticipating a more robust financial year ahead, Russia’s Finance Minister Anton Siluanov has forecasted a 2.8 percent expansion in Russia’s GDP in 2023, a significant bounce-back from a 2 percent contraction experienced in the previous year. Siluanov attributes this hopeful outlook to full compensation for last year’s decrease and the stabilization of the ruble exchange rate. 
Rebound from Economic Contraction 
The predicted growth in Russia’s economy marks a recovery from the challenging economic climate of 2022 when the nation grappled with a 2 percent economic decline. Siluanov, however, projects a promising 2.8 to 3 percent expansion in the upcoming year, viewing it as a reparation for the previous year’s downturn.

 
Read more ....

 
Update #1: Russia's economic situation develops steadily – Putin (TASS)
 
Update #2: Russia brings back capital controls to shore up the ruble (CNN)

 
WNU Editor: The Western media likes to focus on the rise and fall and rise of the Russian ruble, but the Russian economy is more than just that. So here is my recap. The civilian economy is booming and it is causing problems (inflation, labor shortages, etc.). And as for that part of the economy that is dedicated to military production .... I cannot even express in words on how huge of an impact that is having on the economy as a whole. 
But the big story on the Russia economy that many in the West have not caught up on is the Kremlin's priority to re-industrialize the country. I know the money is there to make it happen,  but the big problem that I see will be having the workers to make this all happen. 
Update #3: The Duran's analysis on the Russian economy (see below) concurs with what I know is happening in Russia.
articles.title: How Is The Russian Economy Doing?

This photograph taken on November 3, 2023, shows the Motherland Monument, a 62-meter Soviet-era statue, through the trees in Kyiv. (Sergei SUPINSKY)

 
AFP: 'We're losing': Ukrainians reel from war chief's stalemate warning 
In eastern Ukraine, where another gruelling winter is descending -- along with it a likely freeze in major frontline movements -- one Ukrainian soldier had a grim assessment of the conflict. 
The 35-year-old fighting near the war-battered town of Bakhmut went further than comments from Ukraine's most senior military official, who conceded this week that the war with Russia had reached a stalemate. 
"I've been saying that for some time now already. Step by step we're losing the war," the serviceman, who uses the call sign "Mudryi" (Wise), told AFP. 
"The longer this static war continues, the worse it is for us," he said in a phone interview.

 
Read more ....
WNU Editor: The above AFP news report is a sober read and confirms what I have been hearing. The failure of the counter-offensive to break the Russian lines coupled with tens of thousands of casualties has stunned everyone I know in Ukraine. They expected at least some advances. They certainly never expected a stalemate nor Russian advances in the northeastern part of the country.
articles.title: The Growing Sentiment In Ukraine Is That They Are Losing The War

Military.com: The Army Suddenly, and Chaotically, Told Hundreds of Soldiers They Have to Be Recruiters Immediately 
 Without warning, hundreds of noncommissioned officers were ordered via email to report to the recruiting school at Fort Knox, Kentucky, in less than a week, with hundreds more set to start at the school in December -- a sudden unexpected move by the Army as the service scrambles to boost its recruiting force by 800 by the end of the year. 
The orders came after a breakdown in how the Army tracks how many recruiters it has coming through the pipeline along with retention of existing ones, according to Lt. Gen. Douglas Stitt, the Army's top personnel officer. 
The sudden depletion of recruiters caught Army planners flat-footed, with officials unable to provide a clear explanation as to what went wrong. Now, NCOs will likely have to move during the holiday season and in the middle of the school year, sowing chaos for families.

 
Read more ....

 
WNU Editor: Why the rush to have recruiters? Why the rush for new soldiers? If this does not work-out, is a U.S. draft next? You tell me.
articles.title: U.S. Army In A Rush To Train Recruiters

The militant group Hezbollah launched missile strikes against Israel on Saturday using rockets dubbed "The Volcano," as tensions continue to soar along the country's northern border with Lebanon.

NBC: U.S., European officials broach topic of peace negotiations with Ukraine, sources say

 
The conversations have included very broad outlines of what Ukraine might need to give up to reach a deal with Russia.  
WASHINGTON — U.S. and European officials have begun quietly talking to the Ukrainian government about what possible peace negotiations with Russia might entail to end the war, according to one current senior U.S. official and one former senior U.S. official familiar with the discussions. 
The conversations have included very broad outlines of what Ukraine might need to give up to reach a deal, the officials said. Some of the talks, which officials described as delicate, took place last month during a meeting of representatives from more than 50 nations supporting Ukraine, including NATO members, known as the Ukraine Defense Contact Group, the officials said. 
The discussions are an acknowledgment of the dynamics militarily on the ground in Ukraine and politically in the U.S. and Europe, officials said.

 
Read more ....

 
WNU Editor: Good luck on that. Ukraine President Zelensky and the people around him have made it very clear on what their conditions are to end the war, and those conditions are not even remotely close to what the US and the EU are proposing.
articles.title: U.S. And European Officials Exploring The Possibility Of Peace Negotiations With Russia To End The War

CTV: Exhausted and disappointed with allies, Ukraine's president and military chief warn of long attritional war 
Two articles published this week give a stark assessment of Ukraine’s prospects in its war with Russia. One – by the commander in chief of the Ukrainian military – admits the battlefield has reached a stalemate and a long attritional war benefiting Moscow beckons. The other portrays Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky as exhausted by the constant effort to cajole and persuade allies to keep the faith. 
Ukraine’s military chief, Gen. Valery Zaluzhny, says in a long essay and interview with the Economist that “just like in the First World War we have reached the level of technology that puts us into a stalemate.” 
He acknowledges: “There will most likely be no deep and beautiful breakthrough,” but instead an equilibrium of devastating losses and destruction. 
Read more ....

 
WNU Editor: The two articles the above CTV news report is focused on are .... Time - Ukraine President Zelensky ‘Feels Betrayed’ By The West (October 31, 2023) and Top Ukrainian General’s Pessimistic View On The War Fuels A Debate In The U.S. Congress On Providing Military Aid (November 2, 2023).

USNI News: USS Gerald R. Ford, USS Dwight D. Eisenhower Operate Together in Eastern Med. 
For the first time in decades, two U.S. aircraft carriers sailed together in the Eastern Mediterranean Sea, U.S. 6th fleet announced Friday.

Carriers USS Gerald R. Ford (CVN-78) and USS Dwight D. Eisenhower (CVN-69) drilled for three days in the Mediterranean Sea along with USS Mount Whitney (LCC-20) and two Italian guided-missile frigates.
“Operating dual carrier strike groups alongside Allies and Partners in a dynamic environment demonstrates our capability and capacity to respond with agility decisively to any contingency,” Vice Adm. Thomas Ishee, commander of the U.S. 6th Fleet said in a Friday statement. 
“Our presence sends a clear signal about our commitment to deter aggression and promote stability throughout the region.”

 
Read more ....

Reuters: Hezbollah tells U.S. to halt Israel's Gaza attack to prevent regional war 
BEIRUT (Reuters) - The leader of Lebanon's Hezbollah warned the United States on Friday that preventing a regional conflict depended on stopping the Israeli attack on Gaza, and said there was a possibility of fighting on the Lebanese front turning into a full-fledged war. 
Sayyed Hassan Nasrallah, in his first speech since the Israel-Hamas war erupted on Oct. 7, also threatened Israel's main ally the United States, hinting his Iran-backed group was ready to confront U.S. warships in the Mediterranean.
"You, the Americans, can stop the aggression against Gaza because it is your aggression. Whoever wants to prevent a regional war, and I am talking to the Americans, must quickly halt the aggression on Gaza," Nasrallah said.

 
Read more ....

US Secretary of State Antony Blinken says humanitarian pauses would also allow aid to get into Gaza amid Israel-Hamas war 
The White House is pushing for multiple pauses in Israel’s war against Hamas in Gaza so that aid can be let in, and people can be allowed to safely leave the region. 
U.S. Secretary of State Anthony Blinken said at meeting with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu Friday that discussions about such pauses could facilitate getting hostages released.

CNN: US intelligence currently assesses Iran and its proxies are seeking to avoid a wider war with Israel 
The US intelligence community believes – for now – that Iran and its proxies are calibrating their response to Israel’s military intervention in Gaza to avoid direct conflict with Israel or the US while still exacting costs on its adversaries. 
But the US is also keenly aware that Iran does not maintain perfect control of its umbrella of proxies – in particular over Lebanese Hezbollah, the largest and most capable of the various groups. Hezbollah is an ally of Hamas, the group that attacked Israel on October 7, and has long positioned itself as fighting against Israel. US officials are deeply concerned that the group’s internal politics may cause Hezbollah to escalate simmering tensions. 
The US also does not always have perfect visibility into the communications between Iran and its various proxies, according to sources familiar with US intelligence in the region. 

 
Read more ....

 
WNU Editor: We shall see if Iran is committed to avoiding a wider war with Israel. But I am skeptical. I do not see any de-escalation in the Israel - Hamas war, and tensions between Israel and Hezbollah continues to remain high. The Houthis in Yemen have already declared war against Israel. It will not take much to spark this into a major regional war.
articles.title: US intelligence Believes Iran And Its Proxies Are Seeking To Avoid A Wider War With Israel
